<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
	ws-stokes-theorem.ptx
	Section 3 (Surface Integrals, Stokes', and the Divergence Theorem),
	worksheet 14: Stokes' Theorem.

	Ported from the Beamer deck 03_03_StokesTheorem.tex (in
	outdated-material/notes/, surface-integrals folder): the statement of
	Stokes' Theorem, Green's Theorem as its planar special case, flat
	surfaces whose normal is found by observation, and the parametrized
	case (curl F) . N du dv.  Book concepts tracked from
	sec_stokes_divergence (Stokes' subsection).  Example equations are
	NOT reused from the deck or the book.

	This closes the vector-analysis arc: circulation (worksheet 8), curl
	(worksheet 9), Green's Theorem (worksheet 11), surface flux
	(worksheet 12), and the Divergence Theorem (worksheet 13) meet here:
	the circulation of F around the boundary curve of a surface equals
	the flux of curl F through the surface.

	Authored to the SHARED worksheet conventions
	(checklists/worksheet-conventions.md): paired component="stu"/"key"
	reading checks and exercises; one True/False misconception check; one
	read-along TikZ figure; one modern application.  Standard notation
	(macros from source/notes/bookends/docinfo.ptx); no new macros.  Curl
	uses the del operator (\nabla\times, as in worksheet 9); the non-unit
	normal is written \mathbf{N} (no \vN macro, as in worksheet 12); the
	unit normal is \vn.  Math-valued answer keys are underlined directly
	(\underline{...}); only plain-word answers are bolded, so the pdf-key
	(LaTeX) build stays clean.
-->
<worksheet xml:id="ws-stokes-theorem">
	<title>Stokes' Theorem</title>

	<objectives>
		<ul>
			<li>State Stokes' Theorem, <m>\oint_C \vF\cdot d\vr = \iint_S (\nabla\times\vF)\cdot\vn\,dS</m>, for a surface <m>S</m> with boundary curve <m>C</m>.</li>
			<li>Orient <m>C</m> and <m>\vn</m> consistently using the right-hand rule.</li>
			<li>Evaluate a circulation as a curl flux when <m>S</m> is flat (<m>\vn</m> by observation) and when <m>S</m> is parametrized (<m>\mathbf{N} = \vr_u\times\vr_v</m>).</li>
			<li>Trade one surface for another with the same boundary to simplify a curl flux.</li>
			<li>Recognize Green's Theorem as the flat, in-plane case of Stokes' Theorem.</li>
		</ul>
	</objectives>

	<!-- ============================================================
		 Page 1: Stokes' Theorem
		 ============================================================ -->
	<page>
		<p><term>I. Stokes' Theorem.</term></p>

		<p>
			The Divergence Theorem handled <em>closed</em> surfaces.
			<term>Stokes' Theorem</term> is about surfaces with an edge: a
			surface <m>S</m> whose boundary is a curve <m>C</m>, like a net
			with its rim. It lifts Green's <em>circulation</em> form into
			space. Let <m>S</m> be a piecewise smooth, orientable surface
			bounded by the piecewise smooth curve <m>C</m>, let <m>\vn</m> be
			a unit normal to <m>S</m> with <m>C</m> traversed according to
			the right-hand rule, and let the components of <m>\vF</m> have
			continuous partials on <m>S</m>. Then
			<md>
				\oint_C \vF\cdot d\vr
				= \iint_S (\nabla\times\vF)\cdot\vn\,dS .
			</md>
			The circulation of <m>\vF</m> around the rim equals the flux of
			the curl (worksheet 9) through the surface itself.
		</p>

		<figure xml:id="ws-stokes-fig-rim">
			<caption>A surface <m>S</m> with boundary curve <m>C</m>. The
				right-hand rule links the normal <m>\vn</m> to the direction
				of travel around <m>C</m>.</caption>
			<image width="42%">
				<shortdescription>A dome-shaped surface S over its boundary curve C, with an arrowhead on C showing the direction of travel and an arrow at the top of the dome showing the normal direction n.</shortdescription>
				<!-- Schematic replacement for the deck figures
					 10_9_Fig1.png / 10_9_Fig2.png in
					 outdated-material/notes/ (surface-integrals folder). -->
				<latex-image>
	\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.0,>=stealth]
	% the rim C, seen in perspective
	\fill[blue!8] (0,0) ellipse (1.8 and 0.55);
	\draw[very thick, blue] (0,0) ellipse (1.8 and 0.55);
	% direction of travel around the rim
	\draw[very thick, blue, ->] (1.8,0) arc (0:42:1.8 and 0.55);
	% the dome surface S
	\draw[very thick] (-1.8,0) .. controls (-1.2,1.6) and (1.2,1.6) .. (1.8,0);
	% normal at the top of the dome
	\draw[very thick, ->] (0,1.2) -- (0,2.0);
	\node[anchor=west] at (0.08,1.75) {$\vn$};
	\node at (0,0.75) {$S$};
	\node[blue, anchor=north] at (0.9,-0.42) {$C$};
	\node[font=\footnotesize] at (0,-1.15) {thumb along $\vn$, fingers along $C$};
	\end{tikzpicture}
				</latex-image>
			</image>
		</figure>

		<p>
			Green's Theorem is the special case where <m>S</m> is a flat
			region <m>R</m> in the <m>xy</m>-plane: counterclockwise around
			<m>C</m> makes <m>\vn = \vk = [\,0,\,0,\,1\,]</m>, and for
			<m>\vF = [\,M,\,N,\,P\,]</m> the integrand becomes
			<m>(\nabla\times\vF)\cdot\vk = N_x - M_y</m>, exactly the scalar
			curl from worksheet 11.
		</p>

		<!-- reading-check pair 1 -->
		<p component="stu">
			Stokes' Theorem says
			<m>\oint_C \vF\cdot d\vr = \iint_S (</m><fillin characters="8"/><m>)\cdot\vn\,dS</m>,
			where <m>C</m> is the <fillin characters="8"/>
			<nbsp/>curve of the surface <m>S</m>.
		</p>
		<p component="key">
			Stokes' Theorem says
			<m>\oint_C \vF\cdot d\vr = \iint_S (\underline{\nabla\times\vF})\cdot\vn\,dS</m>,
			where <m>C</m> is the <m>\underline{\textbf{boundary}}</m> curve
			of the surface <m>S</m>.
		</p>

		<!-- worked problem (paired) -->
		<exercise component="stu" workspace="2.5in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Let <m>\vF = [\,-2y,\; 3x,\; z\,]</m> and let <m>C</m> be
					the circle <m>x^2+y^2 = 9</m> in the plane <m>z = 2</m>,
					traversed counterclockwise when viewed from above. Use
					Stokes' Theorem to compute <m>\oint_C \vF\cdot d\vr</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>
		<exercise component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Let <m>\vF = [\,-2y,\; 3x,\; z\,]</m> and let <m>C</m> be
					the circle <m>x^2+y^2 = 9</m> in the plane <m>z = 2</m>,
					traversed counterclockwise when viewed from above. Use
					Stokes' Theorem to compute <m>\oint_C \vF\cdot d\vr</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					Any surface with rim <m>C</m> will do; take the simplest,
					the flat disk <m>x^2+y^2\le 9</m> at height <m>z=2</m>,
					with <m>\vn = \vk</m> (upward pairs with the
					counterclockwise rim by the right-hand rule). The curl is
					<md>
						\nabla\times\vF
						= [\,P_y-N_z,\; M_z-P_x,\; N_x-M_y\,]
						= [\,0,\; 0,\; 3-(-2)\,] = [\,0,\,0,\,5\,],
					</md>
					so <m>(\nabla\times\vF)\cdot\vn = 5</m>, a constant, and
					<md>
						\oint_C \vF\cdot d\vr = \iint_S 5\,dS
						= 5\cdot(\text{area of the disk}) = 5\,(9\pi) = 45\pi .
					</md>
					No parametrization of <m>C</m>, no <m>\vF(\vr(t))</m>, no
					trigonometric integral.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>
	</page>

	<!-- ============================================================
		 Page 2: Orientation and flat surfaces
		 ============================================================ -->
	<page>
		<p><term>II. Orientation and flat surfaces.</term></p>

		<p>
			Stokes' Theorem comes with an orientation contract. Point the
			right thumb along <m>\vn</m>; the fingers curl in the direction
			<m>C</m> must be traversed. When <m>S</m> is flat <ndash/> a
			disk, a triangle, a rectangle in some plane <ndash/> the normal
			is constant and can be found by observation, and when
			<m>(\nabla\times\vF)\cdot\vn</m> is constant too, the flux is
			just that constant times the area of <m>S</m>.
		</p>

		<!-- reading-check pair 2 -->
		<p component="stu">
			The direction of <m>\vn</m> and the direction around <m>C</m> are
			linked by the <fillin characters="10"/> <nbsp/>rule. For a flat
			region in the <m>xy</m>-plane with <m>C</m> counterclockwise seen
			from above, <m>\vn = </m> <fillin characters="9"/>.
		</p>
		<p component="key">
			The direction of <m>\vn</m> and the direction around <m>C</m> are
			linked by the <m>\underline{\textbf{right-hand}}</m> rule. For a
			flat region in the <m>xy</m>-plane with <m>C</m> counterclockwise
			seen from above, <m>\vn = \underline{[\,0,\,0,\,1\,] = \vk}</m>.
		</p>

		<!-- worked problem (paired) -->
		<exercise component="stu" workspace="2.5in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Let <m>\vF = [\,3y,\; 2z,\; 5y\,]</m> and let <m>C</m> be
					the triangle with vertices <m>(0,0,0)</m>,
					<m>(0,0,3)</m>, <m>(0,4,0)</m>, traversed in that order.
					Use Stokes' Theorem to compute
					<m>\oint_C \vF\cdot d\vr</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>
		<exercise component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Let <m>\vF = [\,3y,\; 2z,\; 5y\,]</m> and let <m>C</m> be
					the triangle with vertices <m>(0,0,0)</m>,
					<m>(0,0,3)</m>, <m>(0,4,0)</m>, traversed in that order.
					Use Stokes' Theorem to compute
					<m>\oint_C \vF\cdot d\vr</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					The triangle lies in the <m>yz</m>-plane (<m>x=0</m>), so
					<m>\vn = \pm[\,1,\,0,\,0\,]</m>. Watch from far out on the
					positive <m>x</m>-axis (<m>y</m>-axis right, <m>z</m>-axis
					up): the path <m>(0,0,0)\to(0,0,3)\to(0,4,0)</m> runs up,
					then down to the right, then back <ndash/>
					<em>clockwise</em> <ndash/> so the right thumb points away
					from us: <m>\vn = [\,-1,\,0,\,0\,]</m>. The curl is
					<md>
						\nabla\times\vF = [\,5-2,\; 0-0,\; 0-3\,]
						= [\,3,\,0,\,-3\,],
					</md>
					so <m>(\nabla\times\vF)\cdot\vn = -3</m>, and
					<md>
						\oint_C \vF\cdot d\vr = -3\cdot(\text{area})
						= -3\left[\tfrac12(4)(3)\right] = -18 .
					</md>
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<p><term>Your turn.</term></p>

		<!-- practice problem (paired) -->
		<exercise component="stu" workspace="2.5in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Let <m>\vF = [\,2y,\; 5x,\; 3xz\,]</m> and let <m>C</m> be
					the boundary of the rectangle <m>0\le x\le 4</m>,
					<m>0\le y\le 2</m> in the <m>xy</m>-plane, traversed
					<em>clockwise</em> as seen from above. Compute
					<m>\oint_C \vF\cdot d\vr</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>
		<exercise component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Let <m>\vF = [\,2y,\; 5x,\; 3xz\,]</m> and let <m>C</m> be
					the boundary of the rectangle <m>0\le x\le 4</m>,
					<m>0\le y\le 2</m> in the <m>xy</m>-plane, traversed
					<em>clockwise</em> as seen from above. Compute
					<m>\oint_C \vF\cdot d\vr</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					Clockwise from above is the reverse of Green's
					orientation, so the right-hand rule demands the downward
					normal <m>\vn = -\vk = [\,0,\,0,\,-1\,]</m>. The curl is
					<md>
						\nabla\times\vF = [\,0-0,\; 0-3z,\; 5-2\,]
						= [\,0,\,-3z,\,3\,],
					</md>
					and dotting with <m>\vn</m> keeps only the third
					component: <m>(\nabla\times\vF)\cdot\vn = -3</m>,
					constant. So
					<md>
						\oint_C \vF\cdot d\vr = -3\cdot(\text{area})
						= -3\,(4)(2) = -24 .
					</md>
					(Traversed counterclockwise the answer would be
					<m>+24</m>: orientation is a sign.)
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>
	</page>

	<!-- ============================================================
		 Page 3: Parametrized surfaces
		 ============================================================ -->
	<page>
		<p><term>III. Parametrized surfaces.</term></p>

		<p>
			When <m>S</m> is slanted or curved, compute the curl flux exactly
			as in worksheet 12: parametrize <m>S</m> by <m>\vr(u,v)</m> over
			a region <m>R</m>, form the normal
			<m>\mathbf{N} = \vr_u\times\vr_v</m>, check that
			<m>\mathbf{N}</m> points the way the right-hand rule demands
			(use <m>\vr_v\times\vr_u = -\mathbf{N}</m> if not), and
			<md>
				\oint_C \vF\cdot d\vr
				= \iint_S (\nabla\times\vF)\cdot\vn\,dS
				= \iint_R (\nabla\times\vF)\cdot\mathbf{N}\,du\,dv .
			</md>
		</p>

		<!-- reading-check pair 3 -->
		<p component="stu">
			For a parametrized surface <m>\vr(u,v)</m>, the curl flux is
			computed like any flux integral:
			<m>\iint_R (\nabla\times\vF)\cdot</m> <fillin characters="4"/>
			<m>\,du\,dv</m>, where <m>\mathbf{N} = </m>
			<fillin characters="10"/>.
		</p>
		<p component="key">
			For a parametrized surface <m>\vr(u,v)</m>, the curl flux is
			computed like any flux integral:
			<m>\iint_R (\nabla\times\vF)\cdot\underline{\mathbf{N}}\,du\,dv</m>,
			where <m>\mathbf{N} = \underline{\vr_u\times\vr_v}</m>.
		</p>

		<!-- worked problem (paired) -->
		<exercise component="stu" workspace="3in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Let <m>\vF = [\,3z,\; x,\; 2y\,]</m> and let <m>C</m> be
					the triangle with vertices <m>(2,0,0)</m>, <m>(0,3,0)</m>,
					<m>(0,0,6)</m>, traversed counterclockwise when viewed
					from above. Use Stokes' Theorem to compute
					<m>\oint_C \vF\cdot d\vr</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>
		<exercise component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Let <m>\vF = [\,3z,\; x,\; 2y\,]</m> and let <m>C</m> be
					the triangle with vertices <m>(2,0,0)</m>, <m>(0,3,0)</m>,
					<m>(0,0,6)</m>, traversed counterclockwise when viewed
					from above. Use Stokes' Theorem to compute
					<m>\oint_C \vF\cdot d\vr</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					All three vertices satisfy <m>3x + 2y + z = 6</m> (check
					each), so let <m>S</m> be the flat triangular plate in
					that plane. Solving for <m>z</m> and parametrizing the
					plate over its shadow <m>R</m> in the <m>xy</m>-plane
					(the triangle <m>0\le u\le 2</m>,
					<m>0\le v\le 3-\tfrac32 u</m>):
					<md>
						\vr(u,v) = [\,u,\; v,\; 6-3u-2v\,],
						\qquad
						\vr_u = [\,1,\,0,\,-3\,],
						\quad
						\vr_v = [\,0,\,1,\,-2\,],
					</md>
					so <m>\mathbf{N} = \vr_u\times\vr_v = [\,3,\,2,\,1\,]</m>
					<ndash/> the coefficients of the plane's equation, a
					pattern worth remembering. Its <m>z</m>-component is
					positive (upward), matching
					counterclockwise-from-above. The curl is
					<m>\nabla\times\vF = [\,2,\,3,\,1\,]</m>, so
					<m>(\nabla\times\vF)\cdot\mathbf{N} = 6+6+1 = 13</m>,
					constant, and
					<md>
						\oint_C \vF\cdot d\vr
						= \iint_R 13\,du\,dv
						= 13\cdot(\text{area of } R)
						= 13\left[\tfrac12(2)(3)\right] = 39 .
					</md>
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<!-- TODO(geoff): the deck's remaining parametrized example (the
			 half-cylinder side y^2+z^2=4, z>=0, 0<=x<=3, whose natural
			 parametrization reverses the requested orientation) was
			 omitted to keep this worksheet to one class meeting. Say the
			 word if you want it restored as a second worked example or
			 moved to an exam/homework pool. -->

		<p><term>Your turn.</term></p>

		<!-- practice problem (paired) -->
		<exercise component="stu" workspace="2.5in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Let <m>\vF = [\,-y,\; x,\; xyz\,]</m> and let <m>S</m> be
					the paraboloid cap <m>z = 5-x^2-y^2</m> with
					<m>z \ge 1</m>, oriented upward. Computing
					<m>\iint_S (\nabla\times\vF)\cdot\vn\,dS</m> directly is
					unpleasant. Find it by using a much simpler surface with
					the same boundary.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>
		<exercise component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Let <m>\vF = [\,-y,\; x,\; xyz\,]</m> and let <m>S</m> be
					the paraboloid cap <m>z = 5-x^2-y^2</m> with
					<m>z \ge 1</m>, oriented upward. Computing
					<m>\iint_S (\nabla\times\vF)\cdot\vn\,dS</m> directly is
					unpleasant. Find it by using a much simpler surface with
					the same boundary.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					The cap's rim is <m>x^2+y^2 = 4</m> at height <m>z=1</m>
					(set <m>5-x^2-y^2 = 1</m>). The flat disk
					<m>x^2+y^2\le 4</m>, <m>z=1</m>, oriented upward, has the
					same rim with the same induced orientation, and Stokes'
					Theorem says a curl flux only sees the boundary: both
					surface integrals equal <m>\oint_C \vF\cdot d\vr</m>, so
					they equal each other. On the disk <m>\vn = \vk</m>, and
					the curl is
					<md>
						\nabla\times\vF = [\,xz-0,\; 0-yz,\; 1-(-1)\,]
						= [\,xz,\,-yz,\,2\,],
					</md>
					so <m>(\nabla\times\vF)\cdot\vk = 2</m> and
					<md>
						\iint_S (\nabla\times\vF)\cdot\vn\,dS
						= 2\cdot(\text{area of the disk}) = 2\,(4\pi) = 8\pi .
					</md>
					No paraboloid parametrization required: a curl flux
					depends only on the rim.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>
	</page>

	<!-- ============================================================
		 Page 4: A misconception, an application, and looking ahead
		 ============================================================ -->
	<page>
		<p><term>IV. A caution and an application.</term></p>

		<!-- misconception check: single exercise, solution instructor-only -->
		<exercise xml:id="ws-stokes-tf-closed">
			<statement>
				<p>
					<alert>True or False.</alert> Like the Divergence Theorem,
					Stokes' Theorem requires the surface <m>S</m> to be
					closed. Explain.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution component="key">
				<p>
					<term>False</term> <ndash/> the requirements are opposite.
					Stokes' Theorem is about a surface <em>with</em> a
					boundary curve (a cap, a net, a plate); the Divergence
					Theorem needs a <em>closed</em> surface, which has no
					boundary curve at all. In fact, on a closed surface the
					flux of <m>\nabla\times\vF</m> is always <m>0</m>: split
					the surface into two caps sharing one rim <m>C</m>. The
					right-hand rule makes the two caps traverse <m>C</m> in
					opposite directions, so their curl fluxes are
					<m>\oint_C \vF\cdot d\vr</m> and
					<m>-\oint_C \vF\cdot d\vr</m>, and they cancel. (The
					Divergence Theorem agrees:
					<m>\nabla\cdot(\nabla\times\vF) = 0</m> from worksheet 9,
					so the closed-surface flux is <m>\iiint_T 0\,dV = 0</m>.)
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<p><term>An application.</term></p>

		<!-- application (paired) -->
		<exercise component="stu" workspace="2.5in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					A fluid rotates rigidly about the <m>z</m>-axis with
					velocity field <m>\vv = [\,-\omega y,\; \omega x,\; 0\,]</m>,
					where <m>\omega</m> is a constant angular speed. A small
					paddle wheel of radius <m>a</m> is centered on the
					<m>z</m>-axis in the plane <m>z=0</m>, with its axis along
					<m>\vk</m>. Use Stokes' Theorem to find the circulation
					<m>\oint_C \vv\cdot d\vr</m> of the fluid around the
					wheel's rim (counterclockwise from above), and say what
					the curl has to do with the wheel's spin.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>
		<exercise component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					A fluid rotates rigidly about the <m>z</m>-axis with
					velocity field <m>\vv = [\,-\omega y,\; \omega x,\; 0\,]</m>,
					where <m>\omega</m> is a constant angular speed. A small
					paddle wheel of radius <m>a</m> is centered on the
					<m>z</m>-axis in the plane <m>z=0</m>, with its axis along
					<m>\vk</m>. Use Stokes' Theorem to find the circulation
					<m>\oint_C \vv\cdot d\vr</m> of the fluid around the
					wheel's rim (counterclockwise from above), and say what
					the curl has to do with the wheel's spin.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					The curl is
					<md>
						\nabla\times\vv = [\,0-0,\; 0-0,\; \omega-(-\omega)\,]
						= [\,0,\,0,\,2\omega\,].
					</md>
					Across the wheel's disk, with <m>\vn = \vk</m>,
					<md>
						\oint_C \vv\cdot d\vr
						= \iint_S (\nabla\times\vv)\cdot\vk\,dS
						= 2\omega\,(\pi a^2) .
					</md>
					Circulation per unit of area is <m>2\omega</m> no matter
					the radius: the <m>\vk</m>-component of the curl is twice
					the angular velocity of the fluid. A paddle wheel spins
					fastest when its axis lines up with
					<m>\nabla\times\vv</m> and not at all when its axis is
					perpendicular to it <ndash/> the curl is the local spin of
					the field, axis and magnitude, which is why the operator
					is called the curl.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<conclusion>
			<p>
				<alert>Looking ahead.</alert> Vector analysis is complete,
				and its four great theorems all say the same kind of thing
				<ndash/> what a field does inside a region is measured on the
				region's boundary: the Fundamental Theorem of Line Integrals
				(a curve and its two endpoints), Green's Theorem (a plane
				region and its rim), Stokes' Theorem (a surface and its rim),
				and the Divergence Theorem (a solid and its skin). Next the
				course changes key entirely: <term>Fourier series</term>,
				where functions themselves are taken apart <ndash/> into
				sines and cosines <ndash/> and reassembled to solve the
				differential equations of heat and vibration.
			</p>
		</conclusion>
	</page>

</worksheet>
